  <static seed="1038" source="PCC-ORCCA-ed3/BasicAlgebra/GraphingQuadratics/ParabolaIntercepts50.pg">
    <statement><p>Find the <m>y</m>-intercept and any <m>x</m>-intercept(s) of the quadratic curve.</p>
<p><m>{y}={x^{2}-5x}</m></p>
<p><m>y</m>-intercept: <fillin characters="16" name="AnSwEr0001"/></p>
<p><m>x</m>-intercept(s): <fillin characters="17" name="AnSwEr0002"/></p>
</statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>\left(0,0\right)</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>\left(0,0\right), \left(5,0\right)</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <solution><p>To find a parabola<rsq/>s <m>y</m>-intercept, we substitute <m>x=0</m> into <m>{y}={x^{2}-5x}</m>, and we have <m>y=0</m>.</p>
<p>The parabola<rsq/>s <m>y</m>-intercept is <m>(0,0)</m>.</p>
<p>To find a parabola<rsq/>s <m>x</m>-intercept, we substitute <m>y=0</m> into <m>{y}={x^{2}-5x}</m>, and then solve for <m>x</m>.</p>
<p>For this problem, the polynomial can be factored:</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{\begin{aligned}[t]
   y \amp = {x^{2}-5x} \\
   0 \amp = {x^{2}-5x} \\
   0 \amp = x(x-5) \\
   x \amp = 0      \amp \text{or} \amp \amp  x-5 \amp = 0 \\
   x \amp = 0  \amp \text{or} \amp \amp  x \amp = 5 
\end{aligned}
    }</m></p>
<p>The parabola<rsq/>s <m>x</m>-intercepts are <m>(0,0)</m> and <m>(5,0)</m>.</p>
</solution>
